ON EXPERIENCE:
Hiking through a superbloom out West, I was thinking of this essay I read by Belloc about the three phases a man experiences in his life. In short:
The first phase is youth, in which he takes things for granted, and believes they are eternal. The young man is convinced that his youth is there forever, all material things are fixed for him. This phase ends with every man, by the action of one blow. Some essence is dissolved, some binding cordage snaps, or some one dies.
The second phase is the crucial phase where he establishes his philosophy and determines the fate of his soul. He is done with the illusions of permanence. He sees for himself a definite end — that he must lose. He leans that there is no success, no final attainment, because there is no fixity in any material thing. As he hears stories of the great men who came before him, he admires and enjoys with a full consciousness all the fine things in his life that are flowing past him. The equilibrium of his soul is only to be discovered in marching and continually marching. He now knows that he must go onward, he may not stand, for if he did he would fall. He must go forward and see the river of things run by. He must go forward--but to what goal?
There is a third phase, what this third phase is I do not know, and as I have not felt it I cannot describe it, but if you’re not mature in your spirit, then this phase produces either despair or folly, or an exaggerated shirking of reality, which is worse than despair. Those who fail to find wisdom in that last phase will constantly pretend an unreal world, making plans for a future that cannot be there.
Others become wise. Their wisdom of being older provides good medicine against the insecurity of the soul. Though all things human pass, all bear their fruit. The old, when they are wise, can do for younger men what history does for the reader; but they can do it far more poignantly, having expression in their eyes and the living tones of a voice. If you ascend to the better part of this third phase your business is to console the world.
…
Which phase are you in?

BREAKING NEWS: PORTLAND, Ore. (OMG) the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals has OVERTURNED the law that prohibits recording in the state of Oregon on the grounds it violates the 1st amendment. I filed the lawsuit (PVA v Schmidt) with attorney Benjamin Barr and Steve Klein at the Marc O. Hatfield courthouse in Chapman square in downtown Portland with heavy security three years ago. 
	Oregon Revised Statute 165.540(1)(c). This law prohibited anyone from making an audio recording unless that person “specifically informed” others they were recording. But the law also included special permissions from government to allow for non-notified recording of the police, but not any other government employee.
	OREGON RECORDING LAW STRUCK DOWN: Circuit Judge Sandra S. Ikuta out of the 9th circuit in Pasadena, California authored the opinion overturning Mosman’s order. Ikuta wrote, “Oregon does not have a compelling interest in protecting individuals’ conversational privacy from other individuals’ protected speech in places open to the public, even if that protected speech consists of creating audio or visual recordings of other people.”
	Oregon has no power to protect the conversational privacy of some people in a public place from the First Amendment protected newsgathering of other individuals. Because the law lets government distort the newsgaterhing process and bans entirely too much effective journalism, it violated the First Amendment on its face.
